From: nix-wasm <eric@codebutler.com>
Subject: [PATCH] busybox: timeout — don't mutate the shared parent argv (#35)

Applies on top of 0004 (which spawns timeout's watcher child clone-with-a-fn).

busybox NOMMU `timeout` spawns a watcher child that re-execs itself as the
grandchild with an extra `-pPID` arg, then the parent execs PROG. Stock busybox
does this with a real vfork: the child mutates the SHARED argv to
`["timeout","SECS","-pPID"]`, re-execs, and the (frozen-until-exec) parent then
restores argv[optind]/[optind+1] and execs PROG. The ordering is exact because
vfork suspends the parent until the child execs.

0004 ported the watcher spawn to clone(CLONE_VM|CLONE_VFORK|SIGCHLD). CLONE_VM
shares the argv array just like vfork, but the mutate-in-the-child /
restore-in-the-parent dance does not survive the port: on the wasm guest the
parent ends up running BB_EXECVP_or_die() on the still-mutated argv, so
`timeout 2 sleep 10` fails immediately with

    timeout: can't execute '-p50': No such file or directory

(the parent execs the watcher's `-pPID` instead of `sleep`). This is issue #35's
real failure — NOT the async-SIGALRM/signal-delivery gap it was first filed as
(the kernel async-signal path is proven good by .#sigalrm-test and
.#kill-wake-test).

Fix: the clone child builds a PRIVATE argv copy for the re-exec and never writes
the shared parent argv, so the parent's post-CLONE_VFORK exec of PROG is always
correct regardless of CLONE_VM sharing or scheduling order. The parent's
existing argv[0]=sv1/argv[1]=sv2 restore becomes a harmless no-op.

diff -ruN a/coreutils/timeout.c b/coreutils/timeout.c
--- a/coreutils/timeout.c
+++ b/coreutils/timeout.c
@@ -57,9 +57,17 @@
 static int timeout_child(void *arg)
 {
 	struct timeout_child_args *a = arg;
-	a->argv[a->optind] = xasprintf("-p%u", (unsigned)getppid());
-	a->argv[a->optind + 1] = NULL;
-	bb_daemonize_or_rexec(0, a->argv);
+	/* Build a PRIVATE argv for the watcher re-exec instead of mutating the
+	 * parent's. clone(CLONE_VM) shares the argv array, so overwriting
+	 * argv[optind] with "-pPID" also corrupts the PARENT's argv — and the
+	 * parent then BB_EXECVP_or_die()s "-pPID" instead of PROG ("can't execute
+	 * '-pNN'", issue #35) rather than the program it was asked to run. A copy
+	 * keeps the parent's argv pristine, so its post-CLONE_VFORK exec is correct. */
+	int n = a->optind;
+	char **cargv = xzalloc((n + 2) * sizeof(cargv[0]));
+	memcpy(cargv, a->argv, n * sizeof(cargv[0]));
+	cargv[n] = xasprintf("-p%u", (unsigned)getppid());
+	bb_daemonize_or_rexec(0, cargv);
 	return 0; /* not reached (bb_daemonize_or_rexec _exits this child) */
 }
 #endif
